{{Infobox prepared food | name = Fabada Asturiana | image = Fabada en cazuela de barro.jpg | caption = Fabada Asturiana | alternate_name = Fabada | country = [[Spain]] | region = [[Principality of Asturias]] | creator = | course = [[Appetiser]] or [[main course]] | type = [[Stew]] | served = Hot | main_ingredient = [[Common bean#White beans|White beans]] | variations = [[Olla podrida]], [[cassoulet]] | calories = | other = }}
'''Fabada asturiana''', often simply known as '''fabada''', is a rich [[Spanish cuisine|Spanish]] [[bean]] [[stew]], originally from and most commonly found in the [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of [[Principality of Asturias]], but widely available throughout the whole of Spain and in Spanish restaurants worldwide. [[Canning|Canned]] fabada is sold in most supermarkets across the country.
Fabada is a hot and heavy dish and for that reason is most commonly eaten during winter and at the largest meal of the day, lunch. It is usually served as a starter, but may also be the main course of the meal. It is typically served with Asturian [[cider]] or a [[red wine]].
==Ingredients== Fabada is made with dried large [[Common bean#White beans|white beans]] (''[[fabes de la Granja]]'', soaked overnight before use), [[pork|shoulder of pork]] (''lacón'') or [[bacon]] (''[[tocino]]''), [[black pudding]] (''morcilla''), [[chorizo]], and often [[saffron]] (''azafrán'').<ref>http://www.spain.info/TourSpain/Gastronomia/Productos%20y%20Recetas/Recetas/C/0/Fabada.htm?Language=en{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acocinar.com/fabada.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081110123153/http://www.acocinar.com/fabada.htm |archivedate=2008-11-10 |df= }}</ref> Some recipes also call for [[longaniza]].
==Variations== The Spanish [[olla podrida]] and southern [[French cuisine|French]] [[cassoulet]] are both similar to fabada asturiana.
