The '''North Halmahera languages''' are the [[Papuan languages]] of [[Halmahera]] and neighboring islands in [[Indonesia]]. The best known North Halmaheran language is [[Ternate language|Ternate]] (50&nbsp;000 native speakers), which is a regional [[lingua franca]] and which, along with [[Tidore language|Tidore]], were the languages of the rival medieval [[Sultanate of Ternate|Ternate]] and [[Sultanate of Tidore|Tidore]] sultanates, famous for their role in the [[spice trade]].

==Classification==

The classification used here is that of Voorhoeve 1988.<ref>Voorhoeve, C.L. 1988. The languages of the northern Halmaheran stock. Papers in New Guinea Linguistics, no. 26., 181-209. (Pacific Linguistics A-76). Canberra: Australian National University.</ref>

