West Makian is divergent, perhaps due to Austronesian influence. It was once classified as an [[Austronesian language]].

There is a degree of mutual intelligibility between the Galela–Tobelo languages, and Voorhoeve 1988 considered them dialects of a language he called ''Northeast Halmaheran'', though most speakers consider them to be distinct languages. ''Ethnologue'' adds [[Kao language|Kao]], which it classifies as Sahu but notes may be a marginal dialect of Pagu.

